The phrase here implies the charge that these corrupters of youth unjustly arrogated a Greek name to themselves, which always designated a highly respectable calling. Possibly the Greek accusative plural was used for the express purpose of calling attention to this fact, for rhetoras occurs only here, c. 35 13 and in the very Senatus consultum (cited c. 35 5) referred to in both of the Dialogus passages. On the very rare use of Greek endings in Tacitus, see note c. 31 34.

If so, the numerous emendations proposed cannot be seriously con- sidered as even plausible restorations of the archetypon. But quite apart from this, most of these conjectures, on their authors' own admission, can only refer to a statement of Messalla in a Subsequent speech, which he at this stage of the discussion clearly had no intention of delivering.
